@page "/posts/{Id:int}"

<PageTitle>@post.Title — Bob Ross Blog</PageTitle>

<div class="post-detail">

    <!-- Breadcrumb -->
    <nav class="breadcrumb">
        <a href="/" class="breadcrumb-link">Home</a>
        <span class="breadcrumb-sep">&rsaquo;</span>
        <a href="/posts" class="breadcrumb-link">Posts</a>
        <span class="breadcrumb-sep">&rsaquo;</span>
        <span class="breadcrumb-current">@post.Title</span>
    </nav>

    <!-- Category badge -->
    <div class="post-category">@post.Category</div>

    <!-- Title -->
    <h1 class="post-title">@post.Title</h1>

    <!-- Meta row -->
    <div class="post-meta">
        <span class="author-avatar">🎨</span>
        <span class="author-name">Bob Ross</span>
        <span class="meta-divider">&middot;</span>
        <span class="meta-date">@post.Date</span>
        <span class="meta-divider">&middot;</span>
        <span class="meta-read">@post.ReadTime</span>
    </div>

    <!-- Hero image -->
    <div class="hero-image">
        <span class="hero-emoji">🏔️</span>
    </div>

    <!-- Post body -->
    <div class="post-body">
        <p>
            There's a special kind of magic that happens when you stand before a blank canvas.
            In the high mountain country, where the air is thin and the silence is absolute,
            nature has already painted a masterpiece — and all we have to do is capture it.
            Every craggy peak, every drift of snow, every shadow cast by a passing cloud is an
            invitation to pick up a brush and join in the conversation.
        </p>

        <h2>Starting with the Sky</h2>

        <p>
            We always begin with the sky, because the sky sets the mood for everything that follows.
            Load your two-inch brush with a mix of Phthalo Blue and Titanium White — just a little
            blue goes a very long way. Work across the canvas with long, gentle horizontal strokes,
            letting the pressure vary naturally. Don't fight the brush. Let it glide. Near the
            horizon, lighten the mix and let it warm toward a soft golden yellow. This is where
            the distant peaks will live, and they need a gentle backdrop to emerge from the mist.
        </p>

        <blockquote>
            "We don't make mistakes — we just have happy accidents. Talent is a pursued interest.
            Anything that you're willing to practice, you can do."
        </blockquote>

        <h2>Building the Mountains</h2>

        <p>
            Mountains are not difficult — they're just triangles with personality. Using a palette
            knife, mix a dark value from Van Dyke Brown, Midnight Black, and just a touch of
            Prussian Blue. Apply the color at the peak and pull downward with the knife edge,
            letting the strokes fan out like light radiating from a source. The key is to leave
            the lower edge soft and irregular — mountains don't have clean bases. They fade into
            the world. Once your darks are in, mix a highlight of Titanium White with a hint of
            Bright Red — this warm snow color will glow against the cool shadows. Apply the
            highlights only on the top edges and wherever sunlight would catch a face of rock.
        </p>

        <p>
            Now step back. That mountain is alive. It has depth, it has drama, and it belongs
            right where you put it. You made that. Nobody else in the world would have put that
            mountain exactly there, or given it exactly that shadow. That's what makes your
            painting uniquely yours — and that, more than any technique, is the real secret
            Bob Ross spent thirty-one seasons trying to share.
        </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Tags -->
    <div class="tags-row">
        <span class="tag">Mountains</span>
        <span class="tag">Technique</span>
        <span class="tag">Nature</span>
    </div>

    <hr class="post-divider" />

    <!-- More Posts -->
    <div class="more-posts-section">
        <h2 class="more-posts-title">More Posts</h2>
        <div class="more-posts-grid">
            <div class="post-card">
                <div class="card-image card-mountains">🏔️</div>
                <div class="card-body">
                    <div class="card-category">Mountains</div>
                    <h4 class="card-title">Painting the Majestic Peaks of Autumn</h4>
                    <p class="card-excerpt">How to capture snowcaps, pine shadows, and the golden hour on a canvas.</p>
                    <div class="card-footer">
                        <span class="meta-date">April 15, 2026</span>
                        <a href="/posts/2" class="link-read">Read &rarr;</a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="post-card">
                <div class="card-image card-trees">🌲</div>
                <div class="card-body">
                    <div class="card-category">Technique</div>
                    <h4 class="card-title">The Fan Brush: Secret Weapon for Happy Trees</h4>
                    <p class="card-excerpt">One fan brush loaded with two colors produces an entire forest in under three minutes.</p>
                    <div class="card-footer">
                        <span class="meta-date">April 10, 2026</span>
                        <a href="/posts/3" class="link-read">Read &rarr;</a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Back link -->
    <a href="/posts" class="back-link">&larr; Back to Posts</a>

</div>

@code {
    [Parameter] public int Id { get; set; }

    private PostData post = new PostData
    {
        Title = "There Are No Mistakes, Only Happy Accidents",
        Category = "Mountains",
        Date = "April 20, 2026",
        ReadTime = "5 min read"
    };

    private class PostData
    {
        public string Title { get; set; } = "";
        public string Category { get; set; } = "";
        public string Date { get; set; } = "";
        public string ReadTime { get; set; } = "";
    }
}
